This is the module root tying together the four expansion passes that transform a parsed steno dictionary AST into the flat `TypedEntry` records both renderers (presumably a chord renderer and a stroke/doc renderer) consume. It defines the two intermediate record types, `ExpandedEntry` (Pass A output) and `TypedEntry` (Pass B output), and the single public entry point `expand_dict` that runs the whole pipeline: build the type set, resolve counts, append types, then apply the line-flag pass.

Pipeline order matters and is fixed here: `build_type_set` first extracts `@type` entries into `types`/`arity0`, then every non-`@type` entry (`e.flags.is_type()` filters these out — they're consumed as type definitions, never rendered themselves) goes through `expand_counts` (Pass A, resolves repeat/dcount/computed counts into concrete `Chunk` templates) and then `expand_types_one` (Pass B, appends type strokes per entry) before the whole batch is passed through `expand_line_flag` for the one-liner pass. This means line-flag processing sees the *entire* expanded set at once, not per-entry — it can only be called once, after all entries are typed.

`generic_arg_strokes: Option<&[&str]>` restricts which arity-0 types are eligible as generic args; `None` uses the full `arity0` pool from `build_type_set`, while `Some(strokes)` filters `arity0` down to only those whose `.stroke` matches. Getting this filter wrong silently shrinks the available generic-arg pool rather than erroring.

`TypedEntry.terminal` and `.one_liner` are flags consumed by later passes: `terminal == false` marks non-terminal steps where later passes must drop bracing and skip movement; `one_liner == true` marks the U-variant where every `%b` chunk collapses instead of breaking — both are load-bearing for whatever rendering pass reads them next, and their meaning must stay in sync with that renderer's handling of `Chunk`.

The five submodules (`append`, `counts`, `fill`, `lineflag`, `types`) each own one pass or concern; `fill` is private (no re-export) so its role must be understood by reading `counts.rs` or `append.rs`, whichever calls into it. `ITERATION_BASE` is re-exported from `counts` as a public constant other crate code may depend on for count arithmetic.